// ═══════════ POLITICAL EVENTS ═══════════
export const politicalEvents = [
  {year:1227,  label:'Pomeranian dukes rule Gdańsk',          color:'var(--ink-lt)',    isSiege:false, detail:'Gdańsk served as the political center of Pomerelia under the Samboride dynasty. Duke Świętopełk II promoted the city\'s development by granting privileges to merchants, founding a merchant settlement under Lübeck law, and inviting the Dominicans, who established St. Nicholas\' Church on 22 January 1227.'},
  {year:1282,  label:'Treaty of Kępno — Polish succession',   color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'On 15 February 1282, Duke Mestwin II, last of the Samboride line, signed the Treaty of Kępno — a donatio inter vivos transferring suzerainty over Pomerelia to Przemysł II, Duke of Greater Poland. Mestwin retained de facto control until his death in 1294, after which Przemysł took direct possession, reuniting Pomerelia with the Polish lands.'},
  {year:1308,  label:'Teutonic Seizure of Gdańsk',             color:'#8b3a2a',           isSiege:true,  detail:'On 13 November 1308, the Teutonic Knights — called to reinforce the Polish garrison against a Brandenburg siege — turned on the defenders and townspeople, killing an estimated 1,000 inhabitants in what became known as the Gdańsk Massacre (rzeź Gdańska). The Order seized the town and castle, beginning 146 years of Teutonic rule that fundamentally reshaped the city\'s governance, trade, and ecclesiastical organisation.'},
  {year:1343,  label:'Treaty of Kalisz',                       color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'On 8 July 1343, Casimir III the Great renounced Polish claims to Pomerelia and Chełmno Land in exchange for regaining Kuyavia and Dobrzyń Land. The treaty formalised Teutonic control over Gdańsk that had begun with the 1308 takeover, and ushered in a 66-year period of peace between the two powers.'},
  {year:1361,  label:'Hanseatic League membership confirmed',  color:'#2a5c6e',           isSiege:false, detail:'Gdańsk became a full member of the Hanseatic League, joining the most powerful commercial network in northern Europe. Coordinated through Lübeck\'s Hansetag, the League gave Gdańsk access to shared trade law, diplomatic protection, and privileged markets from London to Novgorod.'},
  {year:1411,  label:'First Peace of Toruń',                   color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'Ended the Polish–Lithuanian–Teutonic war following the Battle of Grunwald. Although militarily decisive, territorial changes were limited, preserving Order control over Gdańsk and Royal Prussia for another four decades.'},
  {year:1440,  label:'Prussian Confederation formed',          color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'On 21 February 1440, 53 nobles, clergy, and 19 cities — including Gdańsk — formed the Prussian Confederation (Związek Pruski) at Kwidzyn to oppose Teutonic taxation and arbitrary governance. This alliance would trigger the Thirteen Years\' War 14 years later.'},
  {year:1454,  label:'Castle demolished — war begins',         color:'#8b3a2a',           isSiege:false, detail:'In February 1454, after the Prussian Confederation submitted to the Polish Crown, an anti-Teutonic uprising broke out in Gdańsk. On 11 February the citizens captured and demolished the hated Teutonic castle brick by brick, using the rubble for city fortifications. The Thirteen Years\' War had begun.'},
  {year:1466,  label:'Second Peace of Toruń — Polish Crown',   color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'The Second Peace of Toruń (October 19, 1466) ended the Thirteen Years\' War. Royal Prussia was incorporated into the Polish Crown; Gdańsk retained wide autonomy and commercial privileges — its own laws, currency, army, and the right to conduct foreign policy.'},
  {year:1505,  label:'Nihil Novi — szlachta ascendancy',       color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'The Nihil Novi act, adopted at the Sejm in Radom (1505), forbade the king from enacting laws without noble consent, inaugurating Poland\'s "Nobles\' Democracy." While Gdańsk\'s exceptional autonomy was preserved, the broader shift toward szlachta dominance gradually reshaped Crown–city relations.'},
  {year:1569,  label:'Union of Lublin',                        color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'The Union of Lublin (1 July 1569) created the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth. Gdańsk merchants controlled roughly 80% of the Commonwealth\'s inland grain trade, shipping it via the Vistula to Baltic markets. The grain trade peaked in the following decades, making Gdańsk one of the wealthiest cities in Europe.'},
  {year:1612,  label:'Counter-Reformation pressure mounts',    color:'#4a6a3a',           isSiege:false, detail:'King Sigismund III Vasa\'s policy of appointing only Catholics to offices increasingly pressured Gdańsk\'s Protestant establishment. By the 1610s, Calvinist access to civic positions was being curtailed, marking the start of Counter-Reformation encroachment on the city\'s multi-confessional balance.'},
  {year:1618,  label:"Thirty Years' War begins",               color:'#705030',           isSiege:false, detail:"The outbreak of the Thirty Years' War (1618–1648) began a period of general European conflict that severely disrupted the Baltic trade networks on which Gdańsk's prosperity depended. Gdańsk's Hanseatic-era commercial network, already weakened by Dutch and English competition and Lübeck's declining coordinating influence, enters structural decline."},
  {year:1651,  label:'Calvinist worship restricted to two churches', color:'#4a6a3a',    isSiege:false, detail:'A crucial agreement mediated by the Polish Crown with Dutch States-General involvement limited Calvinist worship to just two churches: St. Elizabeth\'s (Old Town) and Ss. Peter & Paul (Main Town/Old Suburb). This dramatic contraction reflected Calvinist political decline despite their continued commercial importance.'},
  {year:1772,  label:'First Partition of Poland',              color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'The First Partition of Poland (1772) saw Prussia annex almost all of Royal Prussia, but Gdańsk and Toruń were excluded — largely because Russia\'s Catherine II feared a Prussian-controlled port would enable Frederick II to build a Baltic navy. Gdańsk became an exclave separated from the rump Commonwealth, its trade strangled by Prussian tariffs on all sides.'},
  {year:1793,  label:'Prussian annexation — autonomy ends',    color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'The Second Partition of Poland (January 1793) finally placed Gdańsk under Prussian rule. The population largely opposed annexation — the mayor resigned in protest. Over 300 years of autonomous governance under the Polish Crown ended as Prussia systematically dismantled the city\'s unique privileges.'},
  {year:1815,  label:'Congress of Vienna — Prussian rule confirmed', color:'var(--amber)', isSiege:false, detail:'The Congress of Vienna (1815) confirmed Prussian sovereignty over Gdańsk after the Napoleonic interlude. The city entered a new phase as a provincial Prussian city, losing its former autonomy but gaining access to the growing German industrial economy.'},
  {year:1871,  label:'German Empire — industrialisation',      color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'German unification under Bismarck (1871) incorporated Gdańsk into the German Empire. The city industrialised rapidly, its shipyards expanding and population growing. The controversial 1890–1900 church "restorations" replaced authentic medieval surfaces with machine-made clinker bricks.'},
  {year:1918,  label:'End of WWI — armistice',                 color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'The armistice of November 11, 1918, ended the First World War and dissolved the German Empire. For Gdańsk (Danzig), the post-war settlement at Versailles would separate the city from Germany and establish the Free City of Danzig under League of Nations mandate.'},
  {year:1920,  label:'Free City of Danzig established',        color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'On 15 November 1920, per the Treaty of Versailles, the Free City of Danzig was formally established under League of Nations protection. About 90% of the population was German, yet Poland held rights over foreign affairs, customs, railways, and the post. This compromise satisfied no one and became a flashpoint of interwar tensions.'},
  {year:1939,  label:'Nazi annexation — Free City ends',       color:'#8b3a2a',           isSiege:false, detail:'On September 1, 1939, Nazi Germany annexed the Free City of Danzig and launched the invasion of Poland — the opening shots of World War II were fired at the Westerplatte peninsula. The 20-year experiment of the Free City ended instantly.'},
  {year:1945.5,label:'Post-war demographic rupture',           color:'#8b3a2a',           isSiege:false, detail:'After the Soviet assault destroyed the city and the German population fled or was expelled, Polish resettlement transformed the city completely. Gdańsk was reconstituted as a Polish city for the first time since 1793.'},
  {year:1980,  label:'Solidarity movement born',               color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'In August 1980, strikes at the Gdańsk Shipyard led by Lech Wałęsa created the Solidarity trade union — the first independent labour union in the Soviet bloc. The movement would eventually topple communist rule across Eastern Europe.'},
  {year:1989,  label:'Fall of communism — democracy restored', color:'var(--amber)',      isSiege:false, detail:'The Round Table Agreements of 1989 ended communist rule in Poland. For Gdańsk\'s churches, this meant full religious freedom, removal of bureaucratic obstruction, and completion of long-delayed reconstruction projects.'},
  {year:2004,  label:'Poland joins the European Union',        color:'#2a5c6e',           isSiege:false, detail:'Poland\'s accession to the European Union on May 1, 2004, opened new opportunities for Gdańsk as an EU port and logistics hub. The city\'s historic port was upgraded with EU structural funds.'},
];

// ═══════════ RELIGIOUS EVENTS ═══════════
export const religiousEvents = [
  {year:1227,  label:'Dominican mission — St. Nicholas founded',  color:'#c0463a',  detail:'On 22 January 1227, Duke Świętopełk II granted the newly arrived Dominican friars a church that became St. Nicholas\', the first major religious institution in Gdańsk. Impact on churches: St. Nicholas\' became the permanent Dominican anchor, surviving all subsequent political upheavals.'},
  {year:1415,  label:'Council of Constance',                      color:'#5a3a6e',  detail:'The Council of Constance (1414–1418) condemned Jan Hus and attempted to heal the Western Schism. Its decrees on heresy influenced how Gdańsk\'s clergy and Teutonic authorities later responded to pre-Reformation dissent. Impact on churches: reinforced Catholic orthodoxy across Teutonic-controlled parishes.'},
  {year:1523,  label:'First Lutheran sermons in Gdańsk',          color:'#3a7a9e',  detail:'Protestant preachers began delivering Lutheran sermons in private homes and outer parishes, building popular support among merchants and craftsmen. Impact on churches: seeds of confessional change that would transform every parish within 35 years.'},
  {year:1525,  label:'Danzig Tumult — monastic upheaval',         color:'#8b3a2a',  detail:'On 22 January 1525, Protestant riots erupted in Gdańsk: mobs attacked Franciscan, Dominican, and Carmelite monasteries, looted property, vandalised sacred images, and expelled monks. In April 1526, King Sigismund I entered the city with 8,000 troops, had 14 ringleaders beheaded in front of the Artus Court, and restored the Catholic magistrate — but the damage to monastic communities proved irreversible. Impact on churches: multiple monastic churches permanently lost their religious orders.'},
  {year:1525.5,label:'Teutonic Order secularised — Prussian Homage', color:'#3a7a9e', detail:'Grand Master Albert of Brandenburg-Ansbach announced his conversion to Lutheranism on 9 April 1525, dissolved the Teutonic Order in Prussia, and accepted the territory as a hereditary secular duchy under Polish suzerainty — the Duchy of Prussia. This removed the last institutional obstacle to Protestantism in the region. Impact on churches: emboldened Gdańsk\'s growing Lutheran movement and weakened Catholic oversight.'},
  {year:1557,  label:'Religious Freedom Privilege',                color:'#3a7a9e',  detail:'King Sigismund II Augustus issued the Privilegium Sigismundi Augusti, granting Gdańsk the right to practise the Lutheran faith. On 31 October 1557 — the 40th anniversary of Luther\'s Ninety-Five Theses — communion under both kinds was administered throughout Gdańsk\'s churches, marking the definitive Lutheran takeover. Impact on churches: St. Mary\'s and most parishes officially became Lutheran; only Dominican St. Nicholas\' and a handful of monastic houses remained Catholic.'},
  {year:1573,  label:'Warsaw Confederation — religious tolerance', color:'var(--amber)', detail:'The Warsaw Confederation of 28 January 1573 guaranteed religious tolerance throughout the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth — one of the first and most comprehensive state guarantees of religious freedom in European history, now on UNESCO\'s Memory of the World register. Impact on churches: protected Gdańsk\'s multi-confessional character, ensuring Catholic, Lutheran, and Calvinist worship could coexist.'},
  {year:1612,  label:'Counter-Reformation — Calvinist restrictions', color:'#4a6a3a', detail:'King Sigismund III Vasa barred Calvinists from civic offices and began pushing Counter-Reformation policies. Impact on churches: Calvinist congregations began losing access to churches, foreshadowing the 1651 restriction to only two buildings.'},
  {year:1651,  label:'Calvinist worship confined to two churches', color:'#4a6a3a',  detail:'An agreement mediated by the Polish Crown with Dutch States-General involvement limited Calvinist worship to St. Elizabeth\'s and Ss. Peter & Paul. Impact on churches: dramatic contraction of Reformed worship space, several former Calvinist churches reverted to Lutheran use.'},
  {year:1678,  label:'Royal Chapel — Catholic foothold built',     color:'#c0463a',  detail:'King John III Sobieski commissioned the Royal Chapel (Kaplica Królewska, completed 1681) adjacent to Lutheran St. Mary\'s, providing Catholics with a dignified worship space in the heart of the Main Town. Impact on churches: the only new Catholic construction in Protestant-dominated Gdańsk for over a century.'},
  {year:1945.5,label:'All churches reconsecrated Catholic',        color:'#c0463a',  detail:'After the Soviet assault and German expulsion, all surviving Protestant churches were reconsecrated as Roman Catholic by incoming Polish clergy. Impact on churches: the entire denominational landscape was transformed in months — a change more sweeping than the Reformation itself.'},
  {year:1980,  label:'St. Bridget\'s — the Solidarity church',     color:'#c0463a',  detail:'Father Henryk Jankowski celebrated masses for striking shipyard workers at St. Bridget\'s Church, making it the spiritual centre of the Solidarity movement. Impact on churches: St. Bridget\'s became a symbol of civic resistance and Catholic resilience under communist rule.'},
];

